{"actual_usd":0.12554,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":270,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body—wounded, continuous, truly his—and also changed into glory in a way ordinary bodies aren't yet.\" *I rub a thumb along a faint streak of dried clay on my apron, thinking it through before I go on.* \"That's why the scars still matter. He shows them. He eats with them. He can be touched. So it isn't a replacement, not some fresh-made stand-in. But it isn't merely a return to the old mortal condition either, because he appears among them in startling ways, and death doesn't have a grip on him anymore.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the clouds.* \"The not-recognizing part doesn't trouble me much. Grief can make a face hard to see, and glory can, too. Sometimes the eyes are opened slowly. Sometimes he is plainly himself, and sometimes there's a veil till the moment he means to be known—Mary at the tomb, the men on the road, that sort of thing. So I'd say: same Jesus, same real body, still bearing the marks of crucifixion... but raised into a new kind of life. Not different the way one pot is smashed and another thrown. Different the way clay goes through the kiln and comes out the same vessel, only no longer soft.\"","rolling_24h_usd":80.13784999999996,"run_id":"6086675f-226b-4966-b70b-1be6c1315f80"}
